---
import thumbnail from "../images/thumbnail.png";
import async from "../images/async.gif";
import notation from "../images/notation.png";
import primitive from "../images/primitive.gif";
---

<h1
  class="text-4xl font-bold text-dark ml-8 md:ml-16 underline decoration-teal decoration-wavy decoration-4"
>
  Read more from me
</h1>
<div
  class="md:grid grid-cols-3 mx-8 md:mx-16 gap-6 items-center mt-8 mb-10 block"
>
<article
class="overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow transition hover:shadow-lg mb-5"
  >
    <img alt="Office" src={async} class="h-56 w-full object-cover" />

    <div class="bg-white p-4 sm:p-6">
      <time class="block text-xs text-gray-500"> 2022-11-14</time>

      <a
        href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/asynchronous-javascript-explained/"
      >
        <h3 class="mt-0.5 text-lg text-gray-900">
          Asynchronous JavaScript â€“ Callbacks, Promises, and Async/Await
          Explained
        </h3>
      </a>

      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-500 line-clamp-3 truncate">
        In this article, I show you the basic intricacies of asynchronous
        JavaScript. I take you through Callbacks, Promises, and the famous
        async/await.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <article
    class="overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow transition hover:shadow-lg mb-5"
  >
    <img alt="Office" src={notation} class="h-56 w-full object-cover" />

    <div class="bg-white p-4 sm:p-6">
      <time class="block text-xs text-gray-500"> 2022-08-02</time>

      <a
        href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/how-to-add-animation-to-your-site-with-rough-notation/"
      >
        <h3 class="mt-0.5 text-lg text-gray-900">
          How to Use Rough Notation to Animate your Website
        </h3>
      </a>

      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-500 line-clamp-3 truncate">
        You do not need a huge library to add animations to your website. In
        this article, I bring to you Rough Notation, a simple library to get you
        started with cute animations.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <article
    class="overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow transition hover:shadow-lg mb-5"
  >
    <img alt="Office" src={primitive} class="h-56 w-full object-cover" />

    <div class="bg-white p-4 sm:p-6">
      <time class="block text-xs text-gray-500"> 2022-01-18</time>

      <a
        href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/primitive-vs-reference-data-types-in-javascript/"
      >
        <h3 class="mt-0.5 text-lg text-gray-900">
          Primitive vs Reference Data Types in JavaScript, and their Differences
        </h3>
      </a>

      <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-500 line-clamp-3 truncate">
        The computer does not store all typesof data the same way. But how then
        does it manage these data types, and how is JavaScipt related to all
        that. Read on to find out more.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</div>

<div class="text-center">
  <a
    href="/blog/"
    class="border-2 rounded-full border-teal text-teal hover:bg-teal hover:text-snow px-3 py-2 font-bold"
    >See more articles</a
  >
</div>

